lithograph, supposedly an English response to the Boston protests against the Stamp and Tea Acts, dated to 1774, but is likely to be more recent:
  • Date Created/Published: [1774]
  • Medium: 1 print : mezzotint.
  • Summary: Print shows two men with a tarred and feathered customs officer, they are forcing him to drink from a large teapot. The man has a short piece of rope around his neck which may have been attached to the piece of rope hanging from a gibbet in the background. On January 27, 1774, a British customs officer, John Malcolm, was tarred and feathered, led to a gallows, and forced to drink tea. The American holding the teapot wears a hat with "45" on it, a patriotic symbol referring to the John Wilkes case of 1763. The other American, holds the broken end of the noose and carries a club. The large bow in his hat indicates his membership in the Sons of Liberty.
  • Reproduction Number: LC-USZ62-45386 (b&w film copy neg.)
  • Rights Advisory: No known restrictions on publication.

column24: This print commemorates a mock procession to denounce the famous traitor Benedict Arnold, who planned to hand over the important fortification West Point to the British army. Arnold was a skilled general of the Continental Army but felt betrayed by Congress. After marrying a loyalist young woman from Philadelphia, he finally decided to change his coat and betray West Point for 20,000 pound sterling. His plan failed when the British messenger, Major John Andrè was captured on his way to New York. Benedict Arnold made his escape, but John Andrè was tried and sentenced to death. Benedict Arnold became a Brigadier General in the British army and spent the rest of his life in London, where he died in 1801. Washington forbade that his name be mentioned in any US document ever after, and the gravestones of his father and brother in Norwich (USA) were destroyed. A monument to commemorate his bravery at Saragota was erected without mentioning his name.

Eigentlicher Abriss, als im 1626 Jar die Pawren in Oesterreich ob der Ennss Rebellisch gewest/ Herrn/ Herrn Graven von Herberstorff/ rc. Statthalter zu Lintz/ mit 6000 starck/ alda belägert/ Herr Stathalter grossen Mangel an Proviant gehabt/ und auß Befelch Irer Churfl: Durch: in Bayern/rc Herrn Hauptman Bärtho[omäus] von Tannazel/ Ihr Gnaden 18. Julij/ ebbemeldtes Jars mit 5 Schiffen/ darauf 300. Mann succuriert und proviantirt hat/ Er Hauptmann sich durch die Pauren geschlagen/ und ihrer der Pauren ober die Tonaw gehabten gespannten Ketten und Satlern zersprengt/ und nacher Lintz angelangt. In gleichem wie die Pawren/ so die Statt Linz belägert/ den 3. Tag drauff/ Sturm geloffen/ und nach wehrender 5. Stund/ sie wie verburst [?? Verdurst] etlicher hundert Mann/ widerumb abziehen müssen.

column24:
The print is described in George: English Political Caricature to 1792. A Study of Opinion and Propaganda, Oxford 1959, p. 96:

All the post-rebellion Jacobite prints - quite a number from 1746 to 1750 - attack the Duke of Cumberland. (...) There is a symbolical border with satyr's head, and fire-brands, in the background are blazing buildings, and the figure is given a military dress. It is constructed of an ox on its hindlegs, with the head of a calf; the body is a buther's tray, in one hand is a cleaver, in the other a slaughterer's axe - as in the original. But on the soldier's tunic is a star and an epaulette formed of butcher's hooks (anticipating Napoleon's famous emblematical epaulette). The verses, with omissions and one significant alteration, are as on the original. They end:

"His axe, Knives, Clever, is prepar'd for fight,
And Death & Slaughter are his sole delight
Thus arm'd he Terror all aro(d) doth spread
Had he not borrow'd from a Calf his Head."

column24:
The 'Amen' Glasses and Sir Robert Strange

Geoffrey B. Seddon

From a paper read on 2nd October 2010 in Edinburgh at the
conference to celebrate 400 years of glass-making in Scotland.
The 'Amen' glasses are among the most valuable 18th century drinking glasses. We know of 37 genuine 'Amen' glasses and it has been established that they are all the work of a single engraver. (1. Seddon, Geoffrey B., The Glass Circle Journal Number 5, 'The Engraving on the 'Amen' Glasses', pp. 17.)

You cannot look at these glasses for very long before starting to ponder upon who could have been responsible for engraving them. It is possible to get some clues to the profile of the engraver by studying the photographs of the known 'Amen' glasses. We have no detailed photographs of 3 of the 37 known glasses, but it is interesting to arrange the remaining 34 glasses according to the quality of the engraving. There is a small group of 4 glasses, all with engraving on the bowl which is considered to be of 'poor' quality. The engraver is clearly struggling with the curved surface of the bowl. Three of the glasses are engraved with the second half of the first verse of the Jacobite anthem and one of the three, the Steuart 'Amen' glass, also has a dedication to the Bank of Scotland and to David Drummond. He was a loyal Jacobite and had been the highly respected Treasurer of the bank for forty years. He died in 1741.

column24:
The 'Amen' Glasses and Sir Robert Strange

Geoffrey B. Seddon

From a paper read on 2nd October 2010 in Edinburgh at the
conference to celebrate 400 years of glass-making in Scotland.
The 'Amen' glasses are among the most valuable 18th century drinking glasses. We know of 37 genuine 'Amen' glasses and it has been established that they are all the work of a single engraver. (1. Seddon, Geoffrey B., The Glass Circle Journal Number 5, 'The Engraving on the 'Amen' Glasses', pp. 17.)

You cannot look at these glasses for very long before starting to ponder upon who could have been responsible for engraving them. It is possible to get some clues to the profile of the engraver by studying the photographs of the known 'Amen' glasses. We have no detailed photographs of 3 of the 37 known glasses, but it is interesting to arrange the remaining 34 glasses according to the quality of the engraving. There is a small group of 4 glasses, all with engraving on the bowl which is considered to be of 'poor' quality. The engraver is clearly struggling with the curved surface of the bowl. Three of the glasses are engraved with the second half of the first verse of the Jacobite anthem and one of the three, the Steuart 'Amen' glass, also has a dedication to the Bank of Scotland and to David Drummond. He was a loyal Jacobite and had been the highly respected Treasurer of the bank for forty years. He died in 1741.

In the 18th century line-engraving of polished copper plates was a very

column24:
• Title: America triumphant and Britannia in distress
  • Date Created/Published: [Boston : s.n., 1782]
  • Medium: 1 print on laid paper : etching ; sheet (trimmed irregularly) 18 x 20.5 cm.
  • Summary: A crude allegory of American prosperity and victory over England. Below the image an "Explanation" reads: "I America sitting on that quarter of the globe with the Flag of the United States displayed over her head; holding in one hand the Olive branch, inviting the ships of all nations to partake of her commerce; and in the other hand supporting the Cap of Liberty. II Fame proclaiming the joyful news to all the world. III Britannia weeping at the loss of the trade of America, attended with an evil genius. IV The British flag struck, on her strong Fortresses. V French, Spanish, Dutch &c shipping in the harbours of America. VI A view of New York wherein is exhibited the Trator [sic] Arnold, taken with remorse for selling his [country?] and Judas like hanging himself." America is represented by a Minerva figure, seated beneath a dead tree, with a shield bearing a snake. The shield is ringed with another snake, the Uroborus. The American flag has thirteen stars.
  • Reproduction Number: LC-DIG-ppmsca-24328 (digital file from original print) LC-USZC4-5275 (color film copy transparency) LC-USZ62-45922 (b&w film copy neg.)
  • Rights Advisory: No known restrictions on publication.
  • Call Number: PGA - Unattributed--America triumphant... (A size) [P&P]
  • Repository: Library of Congress Prints and Photographs Division Washington, D.C. 20540 USA http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/pp.print
  • Notes:
    • Title from item.
    • Another impression appears as the frontispiece in "Weatherwise's Town and Country Almanack," Boston, 1782.

column24:
• Title: Down with the traitors serpent flag
  • Related Names:
       Shober, Charles.
  • Date Created/Published: Chicago : A. Judson Higgins Publisher, 1861.
  • Medium: 1 print : lithograph printed in colors, on wove paper ; 34.4 x 25.7 cm. (sheet)
  • Summary: An illustrated unionist sheet music cover, condemning secessionist state South Carolina, and probably issued shortly after its Charleston Convention of December 20, 1860. (See "The Palmetto State Song," no. 1861-2.) Strongly militant in tone, the illustration shows an American soldier standing on the palmetto flag of South Carolina, which lies on the ground. The flag is partially draped over a broken military drum. Two cannonballs appear on the ground around it. The soldier holds a saber, whose point seems to pierce the Southern flag, and an American flag. Four lines of the song appear above the ilustration: "Down with the Traitors serpent flag! / Death to the wretch o'er whom it waves! / And let our heaven-born banner float / O'er freemen's Homes & Traitors' Graves!"
  • Reproduction Number: LC-USZ62-91838 (b&w film copy neg.)
  • Rights Advisory: No known restrictions on publication.
  • Call Number: M1640 .H c-MUSIC
  • Repository: Library of Congress Music Division Washington, D.C. 20540 USA

• Title: Jeff. D hung on a "sour apple tree" or treason made odious
  • Creator(s): Currier & Ives.,
  • Related Names:
       Cameron, John, approximately 1828- , artist
  • Date Created/Published: New York : Currier & Ives, c1867.
  • Medium: 1 print on wove paper : lithograph ; image 27 x 36 cm.
  • Summary: New York "Tribune" editor Horace Greeley, with a copy of his newspaper in his pocket, holds Jefferson Davis's cell door open, releasing him from prison. In gratitude Davis embraces him, hanging from his neck as though from a "sour apple tree." (For the lore of the sour apple, see "John Brown Exhibiting His Hangman," no. 1865-16.) In 1867 Davis was released from prison and admitted to bail, giving bond in the sum of $100,000. Greeley who had previously campaigned in his newspaper for Davis's release, was among those who signed his bail bond.

  • Creator(s): Gillray, James, 1756-1815, artist
  • Date Created/Published: London : pubd. by H. Humphrey, 1798 May 23d.
  • Medium: 1 print : etching, hand-colored.
  • Summary: Round a bare and decayed oak tree is twined a serpent with the head of Fox; he holds a damaged apple inscribed "reform" to John Bull, who is fat and his pockets bulge with golden apples. The trunk of the tree is "opposition"; its roots are: envy, ambition, disappointment. Each rotten apple has an inscription: democracy, treason, slavery, etc. In the background is an oak in full leaf: its trunk is "Justice", the roots Commons, King, Lords, the branches Laws and Religion. From it hangs a crown surrounded by apples, some inscribed Freedom, Happiness, Security.

column24:
• Date Created/Published: [New York : Published by Currier & Ives, 1861]
  • Medium: 1 print on wove paper : lithograph ; image 33 x 23 cm.
  • Summary: A tribute to commander of Union forces Gen. Winfield Scott, shown as the mythical Hercules slaying the many-headed dragon or hydra, here symbolizing the secession of the Confederate states. At left stands Scott, wielding a great club "Liberty and Union," about to strike the beast. The hydra has seven heads, each representing a prominent Southern leader. The neck of each Southerner depicted is labeled with a vice or crime associated with him. They are (from top to bottom): Hatred and Blasphemy (Confederate secretary of state Robert Toombs), Lying (vice president Alexander Stephens), Piracy (president Jefferson Davis), Perjury (army commander P. G. T. Beauregard), Treason (United States general David E. Twiggs who in February 1861 turned over nineteen federal army posts under his command in Texas to the South), Extortion (South Carolina governor Francis W. Pickens), and Robbery (James Buchanan's secretary of war John B. Floyd, accused of supplying federal arms and supplies to the South).
  • Reproduction Number: LC-USZC2-2571 (color film copy slide) LC-USZ62-40070 (b&w film copy neg.)
  • Rights Advisory: No known restrictions on publication.
  • Call Number: PGA - Currier & Ives--Hercules ... (A size) [P&P]

column1: topographical engraving shows the city of Linz while besieged by the insurgents
represents subsequent events in one picture. The outline of the city
corresponds roughly to other maps of the period. It is the only contemporary
representation of this episode that caused Fadinger's death. On the right-hand

column2: very close to the city wall (letter F
column4: one can

column1: see the silhouette of a horse separated from its cavalier. The caption reads:
the main captain's horse that has been shot dead under his body.""
Main captain"" (Oberhauptmann) refers to Stephan Fadinger. The
annotation shows on the one hand that his name was not well-known to the public

column2: on the other hand that the engraver had not yet learned about his

column1: subsequent death. This allows to date the engraving rather precisely. In the
afternoon of June 28 Fadinger had ridden out with some people from his camp in
Ebersberg (today Ebelsberg and a quarter of Linz) for a survey. They wanted to
sound an opportune place at the city wall for the next attack. Herberstorff had
placed musketeers on the buildings close to the wall in order to counter the
insurgents' constant approaches close to the wall and their appeals to the
population of Linz to hand over the city. Two of the musketeers had screened

Fadinger and fired at him.<a style=""mso-footnote-id:ftn1"" href=""#_ftn1"" name=""_ftnref1"" title=""""><span class=""MsoFootnoteReference""><span style=""mso-special-character:footnote""><span class=""MsoFootnoteReference""><span style=""font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;
As the caption says the horse was killed immediately
in his thigh. But his companions could help him to get back to the camp. But only

column3: he would die from subsequent gangrene. Since the engraver

column1: produced the picture in early July
column2: depending on where he was and how long it

column1: took that news arrived. But the image still captures some subsequent events of

column2: notably the fire in the suburb of Linz (C) inside the city wall

column1: that burned down more than 70 houses. Most likely this happened on June 30. Probably
the fire has been occasioned by the insurgents' attacks. But at the same time some
rumors circulated according to which Herberstorff himself had burned down the
territory close to the wall in order to be able to defend the city more
efficiently. This would have been a common strategy
did not report such a measure in his letters to the Elector of Bavaria.
Therefore it is very unlikely that he was to be blamed for the fire. To be

column2: the picture does not blame anybody
column3: but the caption clearly states that

column1: the governor had burned both the suburb and the bridge across the Danube in the
foreground (D). The letters suggest that the engraver is not informed about the
exact succession of events. Fadinger's horse (F) was killed before the suburb

column4: 146–147.

Caption:
A. Das Schloßs.
B. Der Marck
column3:
C. die Vorstat so der Stathalter abgebrand.
D. Die brucke so er auch abbrennen lassen.
E. der baurn leger hinter Capuziner Closter und Galgenberg.
F. Deßs Oberhauptmanns Pferd unterm leib erschossen.
G. das erste leger zu Ebersberg.

The picture shows a person on a hill, delighted by a flower he is holding in his hand. Another flower is growing just beside his feet. He wears a fancy hat and rather elegant [???] boots and coat.
Does he represent a peasant??? He seems to be in an exalted mood, which does not fit to the news of the heavy defeat reported in the pamphlet.
The flower he is holding might remind of a wheel. Is this the anticipation of punishment?
Or are these musings completely groundless and the printer simply used a rather nice cut he had and that could be used for any news item...???

column24:
Full title:
Erste/ der auffrürischen Bauren im Ländlein ob der Ens/ vermeynte beschützung. Das ist: Allerverwunderlichste Außtheilung deß Ländleins ob der Ens: Wie sich die Auffrürische Baurschafft/ auff allen seiten/ in überfallung/ einhelliglich zu beschützen vermeinen.
Erstlich gedruckt zu Franckfort am Main 1626.
Pamphlet contains the peasants' ordinance for military self-defense, the division of Upper Austria into the four quarters, and how defensive measures are to be taken, how many men recruited, how the others shall behave, etc. They speak of their "authorities", meaning the leaders they have elected themselves.
The publisher comments on this only
- in the title-sheet by using the terms "auffrürische" (insurgent) and "vermeynte" (alleged) resp. "vermeinen" (suppose)...
- at the end, in conclusion, saying: "Worauß dann unschwer zuersehen/ was der rebellischen Rott endlich meinung sey/ und wie der zorn/ auch bey denen so gute Christen geheissen sein wollen/ in eine unsinnige weiß hinauß zu lauffen pflege. Gott gebe daß alle Unterthanen/ die ihnen von Gott vorgesetzte/ hohe und nider Obrigkeit in schuldigsten Ehren halten/ darmit beyder theil ein friedlich und geruhig Leben inn aller Gottseligkeit gegen Gott und Erbarkeit gegen jederman führen möge. Amen."

column3: Andreas Vesalius - study of human anatomy
column4: Andreas Vesalius - study of human anatomy
column24:
Development and practical of more sophisticated surgical techniques. The flexibility of print making, as demonstrated by the construction and manipulation of these diverse anatomical image, offered publishers and medical practitioners the ability to represent, generate, and disseminate ideas about the body’s hidden interior and its investigation. The prints themselves were vehicles for the kind of hands-on investigation devoted by contemporary practitioners, embodying both procedures and theory, in there rule as instruments in the pursuit of knowledge.

Prints and the pursuit of knowledge seeks to demonstrate the critical rule printed image played in representing and enabling knowledge production in the sixteenth century. As seen in the examples provided throughout the catalogue, artists, natural historian, cosmographies, medical practitioners, and instrument makers who gathered and interpreted knowledge of the natural world used printed images and instruments to describe and understand the world. Historians of both art and science have asserted that images were sometimes more effective as description of the nature world then actual specimens were, and served as proxy for the objects themselves. This exhibition seeks to demonstrate that prints were also important tools in the process of inquiry, fabricated and activated by their makers to serve as dynamic matrices for argumentation and persuasion.

column4: Anathomia ossium corporis humani
column12: Mondino's major work, Anathomia corporis humani, written in 1316, is considered the first example of a modern dissection manual and the first true anatomical text. The earliest edition of the work was printed in Padua in 1478, and more than 40 editions exist in total. By the 14th century, the practice of anatomy had come to refer to the dissection of a cadaver according to prescribed rules; Anathomia was intended as a handbook to guide this process. Mondino's Anathomia remained the most widely used anatomical text for 250 years (through the 16th century) because it clearly and concisely provided the important technical indications involved in the dissection process, including the steps involved and the reasoning behind the organization of these procedures.
column13: Hollstein's German Engravings, Etchings and Woodcuts, 1400-1700
column24: This woodcut, the earliest known anatomical print of the skeleton, is a diagrammatic rendering of the bones composing the human body. The skeletal figure, animated and freestanding, is surrounded by fifty-tow banderoles, which provide names of individual bones, such as the rotula genu(kneecap) or the ossa pectin is and os naviculars, which form part of the foot.

column24:
Jacob Kempner publisher, The Broadsheet Peddler, 1589, etching, 29.5x22cm BN, Estampes, Hennin 542, Cliché Bibliothèque nationale de France.   
The events reported in the various publications offered for sale by this itinerant peddler date this print to 1589. In his right hand he holds a view of the January 1589 siege of Orléans. With his left he offers a pamphlet account of the Spanish Armada. In his hat is the "Neu Zeitung from France about the shocking of the Duke of Guise." His box contains accounts of the sieges of Bergen op Zoom (also illustrated in the background behind the peddler) and Wachtendonk. This etching was long attributed to Jost Amman but is now thought to have been made in the Frankfurt workshop of Theodore de Bry.
Jacob Kempner (who figures on the print) is probably a fake publisher...

Ihr liebe gutte fromme Herzen,
Die ihr hört Neuwe Zeittung gern.

column24:
Frans Hogenberg after Jean Perissin, The Massacre of Vassy, 1570, etching, 20x28cm, Rijksmuseum (Amsterdam), Rijksprentenkabinet, 309 J 4 fo. 24.
Like all of Hogenberg's copies after Torturel and Perissin, this closely follows the original (plate 11 in Part 2) but reverses the image in printing it. Here, Hogenberg has also introduced a label into the scene not found in the original, incorrectly identifying the figure leaning on the wall in the right of the scene, the Cardinal of Guise in the original, as his brother the Cardinal of Lorraine. The caption is far more explicitly partisan than that accompanying the Torturel and Perissin woodcut. It reads: "On March 1 those of the reformed religion of Vassy are attacked and fatally struck down with frenzied rage and ferocity, men, women and children without distinction. This conformed to the heart's desire of the Cardinal of Lorraine. March 1 1562."

column4: Les quatre éléments
column24:
Height: 179 cm (70.5 in). Width: 170 cm (66.9 in).
Here the four elements are represented in struggle, not in harmony. But they are not presented within one body, but as separate bodies...

Description (art gallery): Personifications of the Four Elements were conventionally depicted as four females distinguished only by their attributes. Louis Finson, however, used a different type of presentation; the elements as male and female, entangled in a fierce struggle. Fire (upper right) is depicted as a strong, young man surrounded by flames. He is in a firm grip with Water (lower left) and holding Air (upper left) down. Air, an almost floating woman, is literary pushed up in the air by water. She grabs fire by his hair and at the same time holding him back with her right leg. Water, a bearded, older but very strong man is seated with his knees up and surrounded by small waves. He tries to push the element of Earth away with his feet. Earth (lower right) is depicted as an older lady lying on her back and grabbing the chest of water. She is surrounded by brown earth and tries to grip Fire by his left leg, who carefully steps over her.

The present painting, made in April 1611, dates from Finson's Neapolitan period and clearly shows the dominant influence of Caravaggio, although he has not entirely abandoned the etiolated figural style of Giuseppe Cesari, called Cavaliere D'Arpino, whose work was also to be found in quantity in Naples, and whose influence can be noted in other works from his Neapolitan period,

The painting is signed and dated lower right: Lovs. Finsonsivs Fecit/ APRIL A^(o) 1611.


Louis Finson (also Ludovicus Finsonius), Flemish painter. He was the son of the painter Jacques Fynson (d before 1609) and trained in his father's studio in Bruges; the influence of Netherlandish Mannerism is strong in his work. At some time early in the 17th century he travelled to Italy; he was certainly in Naples by 1608 and may also have previously spent some time in Rome. It is not certain whether he was a pupil of Caravaggio, but he is known to have copied many of Caravaggio's works and to have owned at least two of his paintings, one of which was the Madonna of the Rosary (Vienna, Kunsthistorisches Museum), which Finson bought with Abraham Vinck (1580-1621), perhaps as early as 1607.
After 1612 Finson visited Spain and then France, arriving in Marseille early in 1613. He was already a painter of considerable repute and continued to enjoy much success in Provence and to command large sums for his paintings. From Marseille he was called to Aix-en-Provence by Nicolas-Claude Fabri de Peiresc, who commissioned from him a series of portraits and altarpieces. For the cathedral of St Sauveur in Aix, Finson executed the Incredulity of St Thomas (in situ). He was later commissioned to paint an altarpiece for the main altar of St Trophime in Arles. In 1614 Finson travelled to Montpellier and then to Paris; arriving there early in 1615, he painted a Circumcision (version, Paris, St Nicolas-des-Champs). In 1616 he is recorded back in the Low Countries, and he executed his last will on 19th September 1617 in Amsterdam.

Text:

Wann der günstige Leser wissenn will/ was diese zwey ungehewre Thier bedeuten/ so kann er das 13. Cap. Der offenbarung Johannis fleissig besehen: darum durch das sibenköpffichte Thier die beschaffenheit deß Papsts zu Rom und seiner München und Pfaffen abgebildet durch das ander Thier aber insoderheit/ die in disem seculo erst ersprungene Sect und gesellschafft bezeichnet worden/ welche sich von dem Namen deß Lambs (Jesu) benennet/ und alle Macht thut deß ersten Thiers/ das ist/ sich richtet nach der weise deß Antichrists/ und demselben die Wunden heilet/ verstehe durch allerley Griff das Papstthumb/ s viel müglich/ bestärcket/ wie auch grosse streich von Zeichen unnd Wundern fürgibt/ als ob sie das Fewer vom Himmel bringen/ und Berg versetzen köndten/ gestallt man in den Lügenden von den Wunderzeichen. Lojolae, Fransisci Xaveri und anderer der lenge nachliset.
Nun haben sich diese zwey Thier/ nach dem sie vieler anderer Particular, Kirchen im Teutschland sich bemächtiget/ auch gemacht an die Evangelische Gemeine zu Augspurg/ und endlichen im Monat Augusto deß 1629. Jahrs/ das verhängnuß bekommen/ die Evangelische Kirchen und Schuldiener abzusetzen/ und an derselben Stelle ihre Brut hinein zu speyen.
Dannenhero diese/ so bald sie in der Stadt auff die Füsse kommen/ sich der Kirchen und Schulen der Evangelischen angemasset/ die Bibliothecam occupirt, unnd allgemach die daselbst der reinen Religion zugethane Burger grossen theils biß zum Exilio unnd Elend tribuliret und gepresset, unnd hätte man von der lieben Stadt Aufspurg billish sagen können: ihre idersacher schweben empor/ und ihren Feinden gehets wol. Ihren 1. Vers 5. die Widerwertigen brüllen in den Häusern Gottes und setzen ihre Götzen darein. Psal.74 vers 4. Sie reissen den Grund umb/ was soll der Gerechte außrichtenPsal. 23 [?] vers 3. Sie sagen/ unsere Zung soll überhand haben ????? gebüret zu reden. Psal.12.vers.5.

column24:
The Kingdomes Monster Uncloaked from heaven:The popish conspirators, malignant plotters, and cruell irish, in one Body to destroy Kingdome, Religion and Lawes: but under colour to defend them, especially the Irish, who having destroyed the Protestants there, flye hither to destroy the Protestant Religion Here


The broadside was made after a roylist conspiracy to occupy central and strategically relevant places in London in order to take over the capital that was dominated by the Parliament faction.
A triple-headed beast brandishing blades, a fiery torch and, most sinister of all, a rosary and 'popish pardon'.


Text below:
O England looke upon this monstrous Thing,
That would our Kingdome unto ruine bring,
Tis framed and composed of three parts
Which are all joined both in heads and hearts:
Doe not behold it with a careless eye,
This Monster brings this Land to misery:
This Monster following its forefathers hate,
Seeks to destroy the Kingdome and the State:
While Church and Kingdome should oppressed lie
Subjected to their blinded Popery:
Long time it walked muffled in a cloak
Till Straffords head was cut off, then it broke
Out of the cloud, but Heavens holy hands
Hath now uncloak'd it, so that now it stands
In a full figure as this Picture here
Doth make it lively to your view appeare,
And in fit Emblems to your fight presents
His shape, his postures, and his blacke intents:
So that if you behold it round about
You shall see how this Monster is set out;
His Spanish Ruffe, and Jacket shew him here
To be halfe Papist, and halfe Cavalier;
His left side Popish is, which on his breast
Is by the figure of the Crosse exprest;
Besides his Beads and Popish pardon be
Emblemes that speak his love to Papistry:

So on the lift side Popish heads are got
Together ready to conspire and plot
Unfanthom'd mischief, and left they should want
Brain to be wicked, and should so be scant
Of knowledge how they might undo this land,
Plotting malignant heads against them stand:
The winged cluster of heads do discover
That Papists rebels from Ireland flye over:
These to make strong their party, do combine
While in one body they together joyne,
Which in this Monster of the times exprest,
And to shew that there lodges in his breast
Nothing but cruelty, while 'tis his desire
To kill the Protestants, and their houles fire:
His double hands a sword, a knife containes,
A match, a Poleaxe, and a torch that flames:
Thus arm'd you may aske what he means to do,
Alas! His dayly actions this doe shew;
He doth intend to change the Vhurches coat,
That masse may be sung through a Friars Throat,
And that the Protestants true Church may grow
Catholicke, and unto the Pope may owe
Supremacie, while Popery that hath bin
Long purged out, may be brought in agen:
In hope whereof, they oppose the Parliament,
Which Papists once to blow up did consent,

As here the match in hand doth represent,
While the blacke fiend did further their intent;
Besides this monstrous Body here compact
Of Papists, Irish and malignants act
Most horrid cruelties where they do approach;
Set out here by the sword in hand and torch;
Firing both Towns & houses where they come,
As they of late to Brimidgham have done;
And like unthankfull wretches have no pity
Neither upon this Kingdome nor this City,
But Nero like would laugh while it did burn,
And would massacre such as would not turn
To their Religion, robbing them of life,
Described by the hand armed with a knife:
Thus under sword and fire this Kingdomes lies
Bleeding, and is this Monsters sacrifice;
While Papists, Irish, and Malignants are
Drawne all into the body of a war,
Who breath destruction, and would ruinate
Church, Kingdome, City, Parliament, and State,
Therefore this Picture here set out may be
Called the Kingdomes Map of misery.
But there's a God that will at last regard
Our sufferings, and give them their just reward;
Let them take heed, here on the side we seet,
They and the gallows at the last shall meet.

column24:
According to George, p. 96:

"The apathy of the volunteers is illustrated in Briton's Association Against the Pope's Bulls. The Pretender leads from Edinburgh a herd of bulls snorting out 'Excommunications, Indulgences, Massacres, Jure Divino, Decretals'. A medallion of Henry VIII has the legend 'Ho ho abby lands again'. The print is bisected by the river Tweed, with Jacobites marching on Scottish soil. Neptune, saying ' the true Spirit of Liberty', presents Britannia with a palm of victory. Soldiers are marching north, some prepared to fight, but one says, 'I wont go out of ye Parish'; another 'Agod I'd go five miles to fight', and the chaplain complains, 'I wish they'd go to Dinner'."

column24: This print was produced on the occasion of the Jacobite invasion of 1715 and was copied in 1745 to mock the rebellion led by Charles Edward Stuart. Important elements are still kept in the later version as described by George, p. 95: „The reactions evoked by the Forty-five are vividly illustrated, with No Popery as the leading theme, especially at first, and much is mode of the supposed threat to abbey lands. (...) As before 'Perkin' (now Perkin II) is in the coach; as before, two of the horses are 'Passive Obedience' and 'Non-Resistance'; the others are 'Superstition', 'Rebellion', 'Hereditary Right', 'Arbitrary Power'. Perkin holds a mask, sign that his Declaration (in which he declared himself 'utterly averse to all persecution') is a snare. The King of France drives, with the Pope as postilion; behind, as footman, are the Devil and two monks. (...) A band of Scots follow the coach with the banner of Slavery and Wooden Shoes. The coach drives over Britannia, who drops her purse and other embems of Property, and also over personifications of Religion (with a Bible), and Law (with Magna Charta).”

column24:
The Princess Dowager of Wales sits under a canopy of tartan (indicative of the alleged influence of Bute), with a face of dismay. Seven members of her supposed 'Junto' approach her.

(Description and comment from M.Dorothy George, 'Catalogue of Political and Personal Satires in the British Museum', V, 1935)
Original design in pen and wash for the engraving (reversed) with this title in the 'Oxford Magazine', vi. 200, June 1771, BMSat 4427, and for BMSat 4874. The words which the figures are supposed to be saying are written, without labels, and seem to indicate the beginning only of the sentences, each terminating in 'and', apparently a symbol for &c. The engraver has however copied them literally.

column24: Pitt stands beside an altar on which he is burning books and papers. Fox stands behind him, protesting at the sacrifice. Behind them is Time with his scythe drawing aside the 'Curtain of Futurity' to reveal a row of broken columns (left) at the foot of which lies a woman with a dagger in her heart, the cap of 'Liberty' beside her. The column on the extreme left is inscribed 'Ruins of the ancient British House of Parliament Destroy'd An D° [sic] 1784 1785 &c.' The altar (right) is 'Altar of Slavery erected in a few years By the Unhappy Politician'. Its face is decorated by three medallions flanked by emblems of slavery: two headsman's axes, chains, and a sword (left), and rods and chains (right). The largest medallion contains a profile head of George III (the 'Unhappy Politician'); the others, beneath it, contain a man being flogged (left) and a man kneeling at a block while the headsman raises his axe. The altar stands on three steps: The lowest and largest is 'Ist Step Dissolving the of the [sic] Parliament of the People'; the next, '2nd A Venal majority in a packd Parliament'; the uppermost, '3rd An Open Violation of the rights of Election'. Pitt is burning 'Manchester Remonstr[ance]'. 'Magna Cha[rter]', 'Statut[es] British', and 'Liberty of the Press'. He turns to Fox, saying, "The day is mine in spite of your Petitions." A mask is slung across his shoulders by a ribbon inscribed 'Duplicity W. Blifil' implying that Pitt and Fox are typified by the hypocrite Blifil and the honest Tom Jones. Fox holds a 'Petition for redress'. 8 January 1787 Hand-coloured etching

column4: The Rising of Parliament
column24: The interior of the House of Commons. The Speaker (left) in his chair holds out both arms towards the bodies of Fox (left) and North (right), which hang from a gibbet inscribed 'Coalition'. He says, "This is a Dissolution". A member seated (right) says, "I wish many Trees may bear such Fruit". Behind him Burke stands in a pillory saying, "This is Sublime and Beautiful". c. 31 March 1784 Etching

column24:
CRITICISM OF THE LONDON ELITES AND THE AUTHORITY EXERTED BY THE CITY COUNCIL AND ITS LEADING POLITICIANS:
A bull in an alderman's furred gown stands on his hind legs, leaning forwards. His horns are held by Wilkes who wears an alderman's gown, while another alderman twists his tail. A dog in alderman's gown, his collar inscribed "Oliver", barks at the bull, two men (l.) point derisively, one dressed as an alderman, the other in parson's gown and bands. In the background (l.) a young man threatens with his cane a stout man who runs away weeping, his handkerchief to his eye. An alderman (r.) is whipping a girl who has fallen to the ground, her bundle of sticks beside her. 1 November 1773
Etching

(Description and comment from M.Dorothy George, 'Catalogue of Political and Personal Satires in the British Museum', V, 1935)
From the 'Macaroni . . . Magazine', ii.1.
The accompanying text explains this satire on the squabbles among the City patriots, Wilkes, Townsend, Bull, Sawbridge, &c. Alderman Bull is standing quietly while Wilkes holds him by the horns, and the "Macaroni Alderman Sir W[atkin] L[ewes] twists his tail". The "Oliverian cur" [Alderman Oliver] tries to seize his nose; Parson Horne, "the associate of Judas", and Alderman Sawbridge, M.P., "that austere tribune", look on and encourage the cur. Wilkes had pilloried his friends and former friends in the newspapers: he discovered that the Lord Mayor, James Townsend, had whipped a girl whom he found gathering sticks in his plantations, while the man of all the world who had served him most essentially was "M------l L------l", but he had been caned and had wept and Wilkes had gibbeted him "to divert the spleen of his countrymen". See also BMSat 4861, &c,

column24:
Thomas Docwra (1458? – 1527) was Grand Prior of the English Knights Hospitaller.

As Grand Prior of St John he served on a number of commissions: he was involved with drainage in Lincolnshire, where the order had substantial holdings and was brought in on a commission to investigate irregularities by the Masters of the Mint. he was also connected with the "search for suspicious characters in London" in 1520. But perhaps it was his diplomatic activities on behalf of Henry VII and Henry VIII for which he is most remembered. He engaged in marriage negotiations as well as financial and commercial matters. (WIKIPEDIA)

column3: James Hind, the Robber who died for Treason
column4: True portraiture of Captain James Hind, the Robber who died for Treason
column19: A further portrait is kept in the National Portrait Gallery London, England: cf. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:James_Hind.jpg
column21: The Trustees of the British Museum
column22: The Trustees of The British Museum
column24:
Captain James Hind (sometimes referred to as John Hind) (baptised 1616 - 1652) was a 17th-century highwayman (who is said to have only robbed Parliamentarians) and Royalist rabble rouser during the English Civil War.

He came from the town of Chipping Norton, Oxfordshire. His partner Thomas Allen was captured when they attempted but failed to rob Oliver Cromwell. He also robbed John Bradshaw, President of the High Court of Justice for the trial of King Charles I.

When finally caught during the Protectorate Hind was charged with treason rather than highway robbery because of his expressed Royalist loyalty and hanged, drawn and quartered in 1652 at Worcester. He was the subject of a biography The English Gusman by George Fidge (London 1652), and 16 pamphlets detailing his exploits.

column13: Ausstellungskatalog zu Ehren von Königin Mathilde, Bomann Museum Celle

column24:
Count Johann Friedrich Struensee (5 August 1737 – 28 April 1772) was a German doctor. He became royal physician to the mentally ill King Christian VII of Denmark and a minister in the Danish government. He rose in power to a position of "de facto" regent of the country, where he tried to carry out widespread reforms. His affair with Queen Caroline Matilda ("Caroline Mathilde") caused scandal, especially after the birth of a daughter, Princess Louise Augusta, and was the catalyst for the intrigues and power play that caused his downfall and dramatic death. He died unmarried. (WIKIPEDIA)

German description according to the Bomann-Museum Celle Catalogue:

"Diese Ansicht der Hinrichtung von Johann Friedrich Struensee und Enevold Brandt zeigt die Situation am 28. April 1772 auf dem Richtplatz vor Kopenhagen. Das für die Hinrichtung aufgestellte Gerüst, wo der Henker und seine Gehilfen ihre schauerliche Arbeit verrichten, wird von einer großen Menschenmenge umrahmt."

column24: 78th Fraser Highlanders was raised in Scotland in 1757 to fight in North America during the Seven Years War (1756-1763). Simon Fraser, Master of Lovat, and son of the 11th Lord Lovat who was executed for his part in the Jacobite Revolt of 1745-1746, was commissioned as its lieutenant-colonel. His regiment took part in the capture of Louisbourg in 1758, the Battle of Quebec in 1759, the capture of Montreal in 1760 and the Battle of Signal Hill in 1762. It was disbanded at the end of the war in 1763.

column3: Medal commemorating the Battle of Aughrim
column4: Medal commemorating the Battle of Aughrim
column24:
This silver medal depicts the English lion trampling on an Irish wolfhound and clawing at a French cockerel. The Irish and French suffered a serious defeat at the hands of King William III's army at Aughrim, Ireland, in July 1691. The battle was one of the bloodiest fought on Irish soil - over 7,000 men were killed. It marked the end of the Irish Catholic Jacobite resistance to William. The Latin inscription on the medal translates as: 'Thus with one claw he strikes two. The rebels and the French defeated near Aughrim'.
The lion had been a symbol of English royalty since the twelfth century, while the wolfhound was an ancient icon of the Kings of Ireland. The cockerel has long been a symbol of France thanks to its qualities of vigilance, courage and fighting spirit. Originally a royal symbol, the bird became a popular emblem during the French Revolution, but fell out of favour during Napoleon's reign. He was not convinced that a farmyard animal was a suitable regal emblem and replaced it with an eagle.

The Cumberland Tankard
column24:
Silver tankard made by Gabriel Sleath (d 1756), hallmarked London 1746-1747.

This silver tankard commemorates William Augustus, Duke of Cumberland's victory over Charles Edward Stuart, 'Bonnie Prince Charlie', grandson of the exiled King James II, and his Jacobite army at Culloden in Scotland on 16 April 1746. Culloden ended the Jacobite Rebellion of 1745-1746.

Convinced that harsh measures were required to suppress the uprising, Cumberland's treatment of his beaten enemy was ruthless. His men searched cottages for rebels, seized livestock and burned homesteads, earning their commander the nickname 'Butcher'.

Culloden was the last pitched battle fought on British soil and a key moment in the 'Making of Britain'. It brought long-lasting stability to British politics and, by depriving the French of the opportunity of causing trouble for the Government in its own back yard, paved the way for global conquest. It also safeguarded the succession of the Protestant House of Hanover, the ancestors of our present Queen.

column4: Abbildung der Statt Linz/ wie dieselbe von den Bawren biß an dritten Tag beschossen und gestürmbt/ biß sie auch ein Loch in die Mawr geschossen/ Doch aber durch Herrn Statthalters wolverordnete Soldaten/ mit grossem verlust der Bawren/ sieghafft abge
column13: Paas, John Roger: The German political broadsheet, 1600-1700, v.4, p.237 (P-1104)
column18: Stadtarchiv Ulm, Orte im Ausland Nr.85 (?? nach Paas)
column24:
Title:
Abbildung der Statt Linz/ wie dieselbe von den Bawren biß an dritten Tag beschossen und gestürmbt/ biß sie auch ein Loch in die Mawr geschossen/ Doch aber durch Herrn Statthalters wolverordnete Soldaten/ mit grossem verlust der Bawren/ sieghafft abgetrieben/ deren etlich hundert darnider gehawen/ theils gefangen/ und die ubrige in die Flucht gejagt.

Measures 280x310, 250x315

Picture shows how the peasants have perforated the wall of the city at the right-hand side, not far from the church. Many of them have entered the city and want to storm and occupy it. Some annotations can be found within the picture, interestingly they are mirror-inverted and since they are rather blurred, it is hard to decipher them. But apparently they read: Die Bauren, i.e. the peasants, and for the first one among those running into the city again "Bauer" (peasant). They are faced by men on horseback. And the first one who comes to their encounter is describted as Stathalter (the steward, i.e. Herberstorff).
The text clarifies, what is going on. The peasant are confident to have made the breakthrough and to conquer the city, but Herberstorff is well-prepered and his most experienced soldiers welcome the peasants, who have no space to dodge. Many of them are slaughtered or captured, and it is quite evident that Herberstorff could have had them killed altogether. But he stops short. He "is not keen on peasant blood", but he releases and exhorts them to return to obedience. The peasants are grateful and promise to try to persuade the others outside to stop the siege of the capital and better go home. "Which might happen soon, when they see the distress". 

German text below in verses:

Wie hefftig sich die Bawrschafft hat/
Umb Linz bemühet frü und spat/
Wie schiessen/ stürmen/ solcher massen
Drey ganzer Täg ohn abelassen/
Biß sie ein stuck der Mawr gfellt ein/
Und ein groß Loch geschossen drein/
Vermeinten alßbald sicherlich/
Der Statt ganz zu bemächtigen sich.

column24:
Abbildung der Stadt Enß/ wie dieselbe von den Bawren belägert/ Und aber durch Herrn Obersten Löbel ihre Schanzen und Läger ganz zerstört/ geplündert und vertrieben/ auch etliche Stück Geschütz/ sampt vilem Viech und anderm Zeug uberkommen/ viel Bawren erschlagen/ und theils gefangen.

Verses under the picture:
Als Herr Löbel vernommen hett,
Was es mit Linz für G'legnheit hett,
Ließ er die Ennser Brucken bald
Wieder aufrichten dergestalt,
Fiel in der Bauren Läger ein,
Welches zwölftausend stark thet sein,
So sich vor Enns gelägert hett,
Erschlug neunhundert an der Stätt,
Erobert ihre Schanzen gar,
Bekam darinn eylff Stuck fürwahr.
Viel Viechs er ihnen auch wegtrieb.
Niemand da von den Bauren blieb,
Sondern sie wurden all zerstreut,
Einsteils die Haut übel zerblewt,
Einsteils gefangen er mitnahm.
Daß sie auch noch mehr Forcht ankam
Ließ er viel Baurenhöf zurstund
Durch Feur verderben bis in Grund.
Ob sie durch solches Feur und Brand
Doch hetten ihr Unrecht erkannt?
Der G'fangnen sich erbarmen thet;
Nach Haus er sie heimschicken thet.
Doch mußten s' ihm versprechen ebn
Fortan unterthänig zu lebn.
Darauf sie dann, wie man thut sagn,
Ihr' Hauptlaut etlich hond erschlagn,
Daß sie s' so schändlich angeführt,
Daß sie gethan, so sich nit g'bührt.
Gott wöll noch weiter Gnade gebn,
so Alle Empörung aufzuhebn,
Daß Jeder tracht nach Einigkeit
Gehorsam seiner Obrigkeit!

column24: This title-page shows an allegory of the church, holding the keys of St. Peter, a cross as sign of the faith and religious books. She is seated between a lion and a seven-headed beast. Two men underneath represent the contrasting yet complementary styles of life attributed to Abel and Cane in the Bible: one man holds a lamb on his shoulder and represents the man of the wilderness, while the other one is depicted as a farmer. Two ovals at the very bottom show animals savely enclosed on a pasture (on the left) and animals disturbed and scattered (on the right), which might me be read as symbols of the church as God's flock.

column24: This is a very famous myth of violence and bloodshed frequently represented in early modern art. The armes soldiers are contrasted with helpless women pleading for the lives of their children. Naked children's corpses contribute to the brutality of the scene. The slaughter of innocent children was also a predominant theme in representations of the Irish Rebellion in 1641.

column24: This title-page represents the new union of King and Church after the Glorious Revolution. The King (obviously William III) and an Anglican clergyman stand right beside Britannia, who is seated on a throne. In the background, several ships symbolize the maritime power of Britain and the fact that William III came across the sea to save Britain from Popery. The English royal coat of arms with William's initials (WR = William Rex) dominate the foreground of the print.

column21: The Trustees of the British Museum

column24: This frontispiece depicts the king placing his 'sacred' hands on his pleading subjects. Anglican priests in liturgical garments stand next to the throne and pray. Members of the royal family and court are also present. In the foreground, further subjects come in to profit from the 'royal gift of healing'. A man and woman hold little children by their hands. Two invalids lean on walking sticks. Royal guards preserve public order. This print is a fine example of royal self-representation in Restoration England.

column3: Sarah Malcolm Executed in Fleet street, March ye 7th 1732
column4: Sarah Malcolm Executed in Fleet street, March ye 7th 1732
column13: Museum catalogue on William Hogarth, p. 183
column14: Museum catalogue on William Hogarth, p. 183
column24: Sarah Malcom was convicted and hanged for the murder of an elderly widow. Portraits of famous criminals were very popular in 18th century Britain and often sold shortly before the executions. This sheet by Hogarth was priced at 6 pence. In general terms, the purpose of producing such portraits was to capitalise on the topicality of the event and the notoriety of the criminal. Moreoever, Malcolm's life represented the kind of cautionary narrative that Hogarth utilised within Industry and Idleness as well as The Four Stages of Cruelty. Malcom was executed in Fleet Street in March 1733, before a huge crowd of onlookers. Although she had confessed to the robbery, Malcom protested her innocence of the murders to the last. Her 'confession' was printed in the London Magazine, and The Gentleman's Magazine and as a pamphlet entitled 'A ture copy of the paper, delivered the night before her execution by S Malcom on the night before her execution to the Rev. Mr. Piddington, and published by him'.

Fighting near Wels between peasants and imperial troops, 22 october 1626.

Text:
Aus Wels Vom 22, October 1626. Dieser tagen sind von Passau 24. Schiff des Schuß wol verwart hinweg gefaren, darauf 2000 mann Pappenheimisch Volck, Welches man vermeint in das ländlein ob der Ens zubringen, als sie aber zu Engerszell kommen, haben die Bawren zwischen den felsen, auf das Wasser Stuck gericht gehabt und auff sie geschossen, haben auch auff die Eck der felsen zu 4 und 5 Centner Stein hinauß gestelt, wie die Schiff vorüber gefahren, auff sie hinunter fallen lassen, sind also vom dem schischen und falle der steinen 50 [?] Schiff undergangen, die ubrigen seind zugefahren, und sich auff das Land begeben, und mit den Bawren scharmützieren wollen, wie oben gemelt, da von den 2000 auch 300 seind davon kommen, haben also die Bawren uber 20000 Comis Brot bekomen und die schiff zerhauen lassen.

column14: Adam Olearii Auszführliche Beschreibung der kundbaren Reyse nach Muscow und Persien: so durch Gelegenheit einer Holsteinischen Gesandschafft von Gottorff ausz an Michael Fedorowitz den grossen Zaar
column24:
Adam Olearius:
Adam Olearii Auszführliche Beschreibung der kundbaren Reyse nach Muscow und Persien : so durch Gelegenheit einer Holsteinischen Gesandschafft von Gottorff ausz an Michael Fedorowitz den grossen Zaar in Muscow, und Schach Sefi König in Persien geschehen : worinnen die Gelegenheit derer Orter und Länder, durch welche die Reyse gangen, als Liffland, Russland, Tartarien, Meden und Persien, sampt dero Einwohner Natur, Leben, Sitten, Hauss- Welt- und geistlichen Stand mit Fleisz auffgezeichnet, und mit vielen meist nach dem Leben gestelleten Figuren gezieret, zu befinden : jetzo zum dritten und letzten Mahl correct heraus gegeben. Schleszwig : Gedruckt in der Fürstl. Druckerey, durch Johan Holwein, im Jahr 1663.
Added engraved t.p.: Vermehrte moscowitische und persianische Reisebeschreibung, zum andern Mahl herauss gegeben durch Adam Olearius, im Jahr [blank]; the blank has been completed in ms.: 1663.
Reprint. Originally published: Vermehrte neue Beschreibung der muscowitischen und persischen Reyse. Schleswig: J. Holwein, 1656.
Many half-page engraved ill. in text.
The plates are engraved by C. Rothgiesser and others.
Includes commendatory verses in Latin by A. Buchner, J.E. Ostermann, and others.
Errata: p. [34] at end.
Bibliography: p. [15]-[19] (1st count).

1st Edition of 1647: text annotating the picture:
"

[Margin: Tortur der Russen] Sie haben allerhand grewliche arten zu torquiren, und id eWarheit peinlich außzupressen. Unter andern /wie hierbey E verzeichnet ist) [S.170] daß sie einem die Hände auff den Rücken binden/ in die Höhe ziehen/ und einen schweren Balcken an die Füsse hängen/ auff welchen der Scharffrichter (F) zum öftern springet/ und dem Sünder also die Glieder wol auseinander recket; Unter den Füssen wird darzu ein Fewr angezündet/ welches durch Hitze die Füsse/ und durch Rauch das Gesichte peiniget/ und lassen bißweilen darzu oben auff den Kopff/ da sie eine Platte scheren/ halt Wasser treufflen [vgl. das Bild Razin??? Am Pranger mit Wasser auf die Platte, Gleb, check]. Auch nach Beschaffenheit der Sache in solcher positur peitschen/ und über die Wunden mit glüenden Eysen fahren.

[Die Schuldner werden auf die Prawe gestellet] Es wird über nichts so sehr Justitz gehalten/ als über die Schuldner. Wer nicht bezahlen will oder kann/ der wird Pristafet/ das ist: We muß bey eines Richters Knechte im Hause sitzen/ gleich wie bey uns im Gehorsam oder arreste. Erfolget die Zahlung gleichwol nicht/ so wird Er ohne ansehn der Person/ se sey Russe oder Frembder/ Mann oder Weib/ Geistlicher oder Weltlicher/ in den Schuld-Thurm gesetzet/ und täglich eine Stunde vor die Canceley auff einen öffentlichen Platz geführet/ und mit einem schwencken Stecken als eines kleinen Fingers dicke auff die Schienbeine geschlagen/ das die Leute offt wegen grossen Schmertzen überlaut schreyen. Bißweilen thut der Executor, wenn er poschul bekömpt/ gelinde und Fehlschläge; Etliche stecken auf wol starck Blech oder Eysen in die Stieffeln vor die [S.171] Schienbeine/ welches die Schläge aufffangen muß. Nach außgestandener solcher Pein und Hohn muß der Schuldner entweder wieder in den Thurm/ oder Bürgen stellen/ daß er den andern Tag zu gewisser Zeit/ sich wieder einstellen/ und ferner schlagen lassen will/ und daß heissen sie auff die Prawe stellen. Wie solche art der Straffe neben andern generibus supplociorum im Kupfer/ so das Schloß von hinten praesentiret, sub lit. A ist angedeutet worden. Ist die Schuld aber groß/ daß der Schuldner durchaus keine Mittel zur Zahlung weiß/ muß Er des Creditoris ewiger Sleve werden/ und dienen.

[Battoki geben] Die andern gemeinen Executiones, so man wieder die Verbrecher ergehen lesset/ seynd Battoki, Nasen auffschlitze/ und die Knud geben. Die Battoki mag ein jeglicher Herr seinem Knechte/ oder dem/ über welchen man nur ein wenig Macht hat/ geben lassen. Es muß der Verbrecher den Rock außziehen/ sich auff den Bauch zur Erden liederlegen. Dann setzen sich ihrer zweye/ einer auff den Kopff/ der ander auff die Beine/ und schlagen mit schwancken Ruten auff den Rücken/ über welches nur das blosse Hembde: und ist anzusehen als wie die Körßner die Felle außkloppen. Hiervon besihe lit. B.

[Die Nasen auffschlitzen] Die Nasen pfleget man denen auffzureissen/ welche wieder Verbott Schnuptobak genossen. Derer etliche/ die also bestraffet waren/ seynd uns offt begegnet.

[Die Knut geben] Die Knut geben/ war für unsern Augen ein barbarische manir zustraffen/ und stehet im Kupffer bey lit. E. Solche Execution habe ich den 24. Sept. Anno 1634 an 8. Mannes und einer Weibes Person/ welche das Großfürstliche Gebot überschritten/ Toback und Brandwein verkaufft hatten/ verüben sehen. Siese musten vor der Canceley ihren Leib biß auff die Hufften entblössen/ und einer nach dem andern sich dem Scharffrichters Knechte über den Rücken legen/ und umb dessen Halß die Arme zusammen schlagen: Die Beine wurden ihm zusammen gebunden/ und von einem andern gehalten/ daß Er sich weder oben noch unten rühren kunte. Hinter dem Sünder stund der Scharfrichter bey 3. Guter Schritte zurücke/ und hieb mit einer langen dicken Knutpeitschen/ was er auß vollen Leibes kräfften vermochte( daß nach jeglichem Hieb das Blut mildiglich vom Rücken herunter lieft/ Dann forne an der Peitschen seynd drey Riemen eines Fingers lang/ von harter ungegerbeter Elendshaut/ die als Messer durchschneiden. Es stund des Richters Diener darbey/ laß auß einem Zettel/ wie viel Schläge ein jeglicher bekommen sollte/ und wenn die beschriebe Zahl erfüllet/ rieff Er: Polno, es ist gnug. Es bekam aber jeglicher 20. In 26. Das Weib aber kaum 16. Schläge/ und fiehl darüber in Ohnmacht. Ihre Rücken behielten nicht eines Fingersbreit ganze Haut/ sie sahen als wie die geschundene Beister.

Darauff wurde jeglichem/ den Toback-Krämern ein Briefflein mit Toback/ den Brandwein-Brennern eine Flasche an den Halß [S.172] gehänget/ je zwey und zwey mit den Armen zusammen gebunden/ auff beyden seiten geleitet (F) und also ferner zur Stadt hinauß/ und wieder hinein auffs Schloß (bey einer guten halben viertel Meile) gepeitschet. So werden auf etliche/ deren Verbrechen groß/ auff solche manier gantz zu Tode geschlagen/ wie des obgedachten General Scheins Sohne wiederfuhre.

[Die Scharffrichter kauffen und verkauffen ihr Ampt] Man sagte/ daß etlicher gepeitschen Freunde/ das von einem geschlachteten Schaffe noch warmes Fell über des verwundeten Rücken ziehen/ und also wieder heilen sollen. Nach außgestandener Straffe ist der Sünder so ehrlich als andere Leute/ mag mit ihnen wieder umbgehen/ essen und trincken/ wie Er wil: Denn es wird in Rußland solche Infamia nicht so groß/ als bey uns Deutschen/ geachtet; Auch der Scharffrichter wird nicht so unehrlich geschätzet: Sintemal etliche Kauffleute sich darzu begeben/ und selbige Handtierung an sich kauffen sollen sollen/ weil es guten profit gibt. Dann weil diese und andere Executiones auch wolhabende Leute zum offtern trifft/ bekömpt Er nicht alleine Geld von der Obrigkeit/ sondern auch von den Missethäter/ daß Er ihn etwas schonen/ und nicht zu hart tractiren sol. Wann sie dann ein ziemliches darbey auffgeleget / und des Handwercks überdrüssig seyn/ verkauffen sie es wieder an andere."

column13: M.G. Schmitz: Der Justiz-Skandal am Peinlichen Gericht zu Giessen: „Ausführliche Relation von der famosen Ziegeuner-Diebs- Mord- und Rauber-Bande“ (1727) von Dr. jur. Johann Benjamin Weissenbruch.
column24:
Ausführliche Relation von der famosen Ziegeuner-, Diebs-, Mord- und Rauber-Bande, welche den 14. und 15. November Ao. 1726 zu Giessen durch Schwerdt, Strang und Rad, respective justificirt worden,
Worinnen nach praemittirter Historie von dem Ursprung und Sitten derer Ziegeuner ec. ec. die vornehmste und schwereste Begangenschafften mit allen Umständen erzehlet ... ; Mit einigen Kupffern / Aus denen weitläufftigen Peinlichen Original-Actis in möglichster Kürze zusammen gezogen und dem Publico zum Besten in öffentlichen Druck befördert durch D. Johann Benjamin Weissenbruch, Fürstl.-Hessen-Darmstädtis. Vormunds-Raht, auch Ober-Schultheissen und Peinl. Gerichts-Assessoren daselbst.

1727 erschien das Werk „Ausführliche Relation von der famosen Ziegeuner-Diebs- Mord- und Rauberbande“ von Dr. jur. Johann Benjamin Weissenbruch (verfahrensbeteiligter Richter, der wohl im Auftrag des Landgrafen von Hessen durch dieses Buch die Massenhinrichtung publik machen sollte – wohl weniger zur Rechtfertigung als zur Abschreckung. Nach meiner Kenntnis (bitte beachten Sie hierzu in der avisierten 2. email meine „Warnungen vor mir“) war dieses Verfahren der (abgesehen von Massenaburteilungen in Kriegszeiten) Prozess mit der höchsten Zahl an vollstreckten Todesurteilen im Rahmen eines einzigen Prozesses (es wurden 25 Sinti hingerichtet (nach meiner Interpretation und aus heutiger Sicht: unschuldig). – Im zugrunde liegenden Original  (das m.W. im Internet digital komplett eingestellt ist) und in meinen kommentierten Überarbeitung „Der Justiz-Skandal am Peinlichen Gericht zu Giesen“ finden sich auch zeitgenössische Abbildungen, u.a. von der Massenhinrichtung.

column3: An Exact View of the Battle of Culloden

column24: Victorious battles were frequently represented in printed royal propaganda. The 18th century was very much concerned with military skills and discipline, and a victory over rebel armies proved the ruler's superiority and legitimacy. Battle scenes (in the style of landscape painting) became much more popular and influential than depictions of court trials and executions.

column24: This print celebrates the victorious battle of Culloden and praises the Duke's fight for English liberty. The inscriptions are both in French and English. The fact that the Duke drew his "vengeful sword" and did not spare the rebels is seen as a necessary deed to restore peace. The engraving was made in January 1747.

column3: A Hymn to the Pillory (Daniel Defoe)

column24: Defoe was punished to the pillory for his pamphlet "The shortest way with the Dissenters", which attacked the King's religious policy and the Anglican episcopacy. He responded to this humiliation with his "hymn to the pillory".

column4: Daniel Defoe is standing in the pillory while soldiers have to restrain crowds from throwing flowers at him
column20: from Hutchinson's "History of the British Nation"
column24: Daniel Defoe (1661-1731). An English writer who is best known as a novelist and the author of Robinson Crusoe (1719) and several other fictional autobiographies. Defoe's contemporaries did not know him as a novelist, as all his texts were anonymous, and most were not attributed to him until several decades after his death. Like his parents, he was a Protestant Dissenter, and he first became known as a writer for his "Shortest way with dissenters" (1703), a satirical defence of his co-eligionists, for the writing of which he was placed in the pillory.

column4: Tomb of Maria Clementina Sobieska
column24: Pietro Bracci perpetuated the memory of the princess Maria Clementina Sobieska who married to James Stuart, the Old Pretender, who was living in exile in Rome. Her crusade for the Catholic faith earned her the extreme honour, one usually reserved to popes, of being buried in St Peter's at the Vatican. Bracci's work is a gaudy example of the Italian passion for polychromy and composite materials. The medallion contains a portrait of the defunct in mosaic; and in the midst of an orgy of coloured marbles, gilt bronze and stucco, the lovely figure of Charity (or the Love of God) holding a flaming heart in her hand is carved in pure white marble.

column3: The Beheading of Queen Anne Bullen [Boleyn]
column4: The Beheading of Queen Anne Bullen [Boleyn]
Nils Dackes avhuggna huvud, uppspikat på en påle. Teckning ur Johan Petri Klints "Den swenska krönicka om Kongungh Göstaffs rigemente ifrån anno 1520 intill 1560".
column17: In 16th century chronicle by Joen Petri Klint
column24:
Impiled head of Nils Dacke, the leader of the Dacke-War in Smaland in 1542-43.

The uprising started in June 1542 with the assassination of more sheriffs and tax collectors. Gustav Vasa underestimated the military prowess of the peasants and sent his German mercenaries to quell the revolt. The landsknechts were, however, unsuited for battle in the rugged forests and suffered heavy losses. Dacke had devised defensive tactics that allowed the peasants to use their steel crossbows with devastating effect. Dacke's successes helped spread the revolt over all the southern provinces of Sweden. The situation was so serious that the king was forced to sue for peace, and a one-year ceasefire was signed on 8. November. During the ceasefire, Dacke was the de facto ruler of most of southern Sweden and received offers of foreign support from the Elector Palatine Frederick II (who was the son in law of Christian II and claimed the Swedish throne) and Duke Albrecht of Mecklenburg. He reinstated the ceremonies of the Roman Catholic Church and reopened the cross border trade in the areas under his control. With Danish support Gustav Vasa mounted an invasion of Mecklenburg which neutralised the German threat.

The king broke the ceasefire in January 1543 and sent a new and larger army into the rebellious area. Royal propaganda had been spread to win over the population and turn them against Dacke. Dacke himself had become overconfident after earlier successes and met the Royal army in a pitched battle in March. The trained soldiers fighting on their own terms shattered the peasant army, and Dacke was severely injured. After this defeat, the rebellion was effectively over and Dacke became an outlaw.

Dacke was shot and killed in the high summer of 1543 in the forests which, at the time, surrounded the southeastern border between Sweden and Denmark (nowadays southern Swedish provinces Småland and Blekinge). According to contemporary sources, he had been injured in both legs by hits from the king's crossbows during the decisive battle a few months earlier, his forces had been routed and he was likely trying to escape from the king's mercenaries. There is no doubt that he was killed on the spot.

Dacke was executed posthumously, quartered, and his limbs were sent for public display in larger communities that had supported him during the rebellion. Gustav Vasa ordered the annihilation of Dacke's entire family, but showed some leniency against those who had given themselves up. Thus, the unity of the realm was restored.

As a result of the war the king was henceforth more careful when dealing with his subjects. The reliance on foreign mercenaries in the army was reduced in favour of soldiers of Swedish extraction (many of which were recruited in Småland) and this laid the foundation for Sweden's military successes in later wars. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nils_Dacke)

More information is needed about the Klint and his chronicle. For whom was it composed and how far did it circulate?

column19:
Johann Friedrich Corvinus: Anabaptisticum Et Enthusiasticum
    Pantheon, Und Geistliches Rüst-Hauß Wider die Alten Quacker, Und
    Neuen Frey-Geister, Welche die Kirche Gottes zeithero verunruhiget,
    und bestürmet, auch treue Lehrer und Prediger Göttlichen Worts,
    verachtet, verleumdet, gelästert und verfolget haben, mit vielen zur
    Sache dienlichen und nützlichen Kupffern, bloß zu Gottes Ehre.
    [Cöthen] 1701-1702.
column20:
Historia Fanaticorum Oder eine vollkommene Relation und Wissenschaft von den Alten Anabaptisten und Neuen Qväkern, So die Summa ist alles dessen/ was von ihren mehrentheils blasphemischen Opinionen/ gefährlichen Practiken/ und gottlosen Attentaten, alles Civil Guvernement, beydes in der Kirchen/ und in gemeinem Weltwesen zu subvertiren, kund worden/ Samt ihren tollen närrischen Spielen/ lächerlichen Actionen und Gebehrden/ genugsam einen nüchtern Christen-Menschen bestürzt zu machen/ Welches den Todt gleichsam und das faule stinckende Aaß der Fanatischen Lehre zeigen kan; Publiciret in Londen Anno 1660. mit der Approbation unterschiedener Englischen Theologen/ Nun aber Dem Vaterland Preussischer Nation, und besonders hiesiger Stadt Dantzig zum besten aus dem Englischen treulich vertiret, und ins Deutsche übersetzet/ von Benedict Figken, Predigern an der Pfar-Kirchen daselbsten/ Dem mit beygefüget ist zur Zugabe/ Was mit etzlichen Qväkern hiesiges Orts/ in Dantzig vor kurzer Zeit paßiret ist.
[Aufgeteilt in 2 Bücher: 1) Der Alte Anabaptist Oder Eine Kurtze Historie Von den Anabaptisten in Germanien. Das erste Buch. 2) Der Newe Qväker oder Eine kurtze Historie von den Qväkern in England. Das Ander Buch], between p.70 and 71.

[Cöthen] 1701-1702 [p. 0350 pdf Münchner Digitalisierungszentrum]

column3: The Repeal, or the Funeral Procession of Miss Americ.Stamp
column4: The Repeal, or the Funeral Procession of Miss Americ.Stamp
column24:
George, p. 135:

"Wilson responded with The Repeal, Or, The Funeral of Miss Americ - Stamp published, he says, within then minutes of the repeal of the Act (8 March). Here then is one of the very few prints known to have been officially inspired. Its success was immediate and remarkable. Wilson states that in four days he sold above 2,000 at a shilling apiece. He could not keep pace with the demand and on the fifth day two pirated copies came out at half the price: 'credible person' told him that 16,000 of these were sold. Actually, there are four piracies in the British Museum, besides a reduced copy in the Antidote. Seven versions were exhibited in the New York Public Library in November 1939. It was described in the newspapers and a long facetious description is quoted in Benjamin Franklin's Memoirs. A funeral procession makes its way towards a tomb inscirbed 'Within this Family Vault; Lie interred, it is to be hoped never to rise again, The Star Chamber Court, Ship Money - Excise Money and all Imports without Parliament, The Act de Haeritico [sic] Comburendo, Hearth Mon Gener Warrants And [a blank for Miss Americ Stamp] which tended to alienate the Affection of English-men to their Country'. Above the tomb two skulls of traitors (as those displayed on Temple Bar) associate not only Bute but the Stamp Act with Jacobitism. Anti-Sejanus heads the procession reading the burial service, two legal bêtes noires follow, Wedderburn and Fletcher Norton, with black processional flags decorated with 'Stamps' - a device of Scottish thistle (p. 136) and Jacobite white rose. Grenville carries the infant's coffin, and is followed by the chief mourner, Bute - 'Sejanus'. Next come Bedford and Temple, Halifax and Sandwich, and two bishops. Now that Non Intercourse is over, the Thames-side warehouses are open again, ships are ready to sail - the Rockingham, the Grafton, the Conway, named after those who had carried repeal. A big chest is being shipped containing 'a statue of Mr Pitt'. Wilson's two prints embody the main points of the propaganda against the Stamp Act - the only American tax except the Tea Tax to be mentioned in the prints. They stress the firmly held delusions that Bute and his following were responsible for 'stamping' America, that the Stamp Act and General Warrants were linked tyrannies, and that the causes of America and Wilkes were one."

column17: Государственный исторический музей, Инв.  №  52789  И   Ш   61108
column24:
Иллюстрация к «Сказанию о наказании Каину за убийство брата»..  Середина  XIX   в. Неизвестный  художник. Чернила,   темпера,  золото.   56,9x40

 

Внизу текст в 7 строк: «Рече Господь к Каину: Каине, где брат твой Аввель? Господи, не страждь есмь брату своему. Еще рече Господь... и велик и премудр Господь». Под рамкой листа текст в 2 строки: «Кто тя, брате, сему злу научи, еже клеветати на брата своего? О сем бо, брате, и во Апостоле пишет: не любяи брата, не любит Бога,   осуждай   брата   своего, закон бо судиши, и сам зле постраждеши,  покрый братия согрешения, а  Бог твоя покрыет». Инв.  №  52789  И   Ш   61108 Поступило от А.  А.  Бахрушина в  1921  г. На картинке представлен библейский рассказ   о  братоубийстве   в   апокрифической трактовке.    Главное   внимание   художник уделяет показу страданий, испытываемых Каином после преступления, и посланных ему наказаний. Сюжет  не  имеет  аналогий

column3: Расправа воеводы Мещеринова с участниками Соловецкого восстания 1668—1676 гг.
column4: Изображение расправы воеводы Мещеринова с участниками Соловецкого восстания 1668—1676 гг. (Voivoda Meshcherinov Putting Down the Solovki Rebellion)
column24:
Изображение расправы воеводы Мещеринова с участниками Соловецкого восстания 1668—1676  гг.  

Начало  XIX   в. Художник   М.   В.   Григорьев  (?) Чернила,  темпера.  69x102

 

Названия нет. Пояснительные надписи (в порядке последовательности эпизодов): «Осади воевода обитель и постави наряд пушечен мног, и сташа бити по обители боем огненным денно же и нощно, не усы-па ючи»; «воевода царской Иван Мещеринов»; «вой царские»; «изшед навет... с кресты, иконы и кандилы и убия их»; «мученники за древлеблагочестие»; «игумен и келарь, влекомые воями к Мещери-нову на мучения»; «ииоци иже во мразы лютейшие с монастыря изгнаша в губу морскую и их в льдах заморози, и лежах тела их 1 лета нетленны, прильпе бо"плоть к кости и недвигнуся суставы»; «царю же Алексию Михайловичи», боляще сущу, и мня, си аще за грех пред преподобными наказание приях, и написа грамоту вручи царице Наталии Кириловне, да не мотчав ко Мещеринову отправит, да престанет обитель восвати»; «гонец царской»; «гонец Мещеринова»; «град Вологда»; «гонец царской вегрети на пути во граде Вологде гонца от воеводы Мещеринова с грамотою о раззорении монастыря». Приобретено  «на  торгу»  в   1909 г. Литература:   Иткина  I,  с.  38;  Иткина  II, с.  255

 

На картинках изображены события подавления выступления монахов Соловецкого монастыря против реформы патриарха Никона. Оба листа иллюстрируют книгу С. Денисова «История об отцех и страдальцех соловецких», написанную в 1730-х гг. В настоящее время выявлено шесть вариантов настенных листов на данный сюжет, из которых три обнаруживают непосредственную зависимость друг от друга и восходят к общему оригиналу и три возникли независимо от этой группы, хотя их создатели творили, придерживаясь общей традиции воплощения данного  сюжета.

Картинка (кат. 88) обнаруживает текстологическую и художественную зависимость от рукописной повести «Описание лицевое великой осады и разорения монастыря соловецкого», написанной в конце XVIII в. и вышедшей из московской мастерской, где в конце XVIII —начале XIX в. работал мастер М. В. Григорьев. Предположительная атрибуция картинки художнику Григорьеву сделана на основании стилистической близости ее с подписными произведениями мастера. (Подробно об  этом  см.:   Иткина   I,   Иткина   П.)

Внизу текст в 7 строк: «Рече Господь к Каину: Каине, где брат твой Аввель? Господи, не страждь есмь брату своему. Еще рече Господь... и велик и премудр Господь». Под рамкой листа текст в 2 строки: «Кто тя, брате, сему злу научи, еже клеветати на брата своего? О сем бо, брате, и во Апостоле пишет: не любяи брата, не любит Бога,   осуждай   брата   своего, закон бо судиши, и сам зле постраждеши,  покрый братия согрешения, а  Бог твоя покрыет». Инв.  №  52789  И   Ш   61108 Поступило от А.  А.  Бахрушина в  1921  г. На картинке представлен библейский рассказ   о  братоубийстве   в   апокрифической трактовке.    Главное   внимание   художник уделяет показу страданий, испытываемых Каином после преступления, и посланных ему наказаний. column4: Жертвоприношение Авраама (Adam's sacrifice)
column20:
Приобретено у П. С. Кузнецова в 1902 г. Изображен жертвенник, на котором распростерто тело Исаака. Рядом стоит Авраам с занесенным ножом, а над ним на облачке — ангел, останавливающий руку Авраама.

Картинка является иллюстрацией библейской легенды. В миниатюрах рукописей сюжет встречается редко, известен в «Псковской Палее» 1477 г.— ГИМ, Син. 210, л. 91. В гравированные библии сюжет включался постоянно: Ровинский 1, т. 3, с. 242, 261, 269; Библия/Гравюры Д. Пастухова и Г. Тепчегорского. М., 1720—1730. Л. 14. По отношению к печатным изданиям и к миниатюре рисунок полностью самостоятелен.

column3: Schilo Sabothoj (German title, illegible in reproduction)
column4: Schilo Sabothoj (German title, illegible in reproduction)
column18: Jewish Museum London Catalogue Number: AR 2242
column19: reproduced in Scholem, The Mystical Messiah (check exact referece)
column24:
Description by museum: The Jewish mystic and claimed Messiah Shabbethai Zevi (1626-1676) wearing a crown of laurels and holding a wand, leading a procession of Europeans to receive homage from a group of Orientals; on the right are two other scenes, in one of which an angel is appearing to him; across the picture is engraved 'Schalo Sabottoi Natus 5547;' the text above is in German.

The name on the banner is rather Schilo Sabothoj and refers to another prophet than Sabbatai Zwi, but according to a correspondance between two Rabbis in the Ottoman Empire Schilo Sabathi appeared in Tartary and presented Saba Sabathi (Probably Sabbatai Zewi) as his precursor who would have been brutally murdered by the Ottomans. The senseless date (natus 5547) also comes from this correspondance.

    Hung in P26-27 (7) George Washington, Esq.r, general and commander in chief of the Continental Army in America : print (mezzotint, hand-colored), drawn from life by Alexander Campbell, published by C. Shepherd, 1775 Sept. 9. 1 print, framed; plate mark 36 x 25 cm, in frame 49 x 40 cm
    In lower right-hand margin: 85.
    Hart number 721a; Morgan and Fielding p. 53.
    44WM-24.

    * ATTENTION:

    of this three-quarter portrait at least three versions or stages are known; one of the printing plates is signed by German engraver Johann Martin Will, but it remains unclear if he created all three existing versions; Charles Henry Hart wrote in 1904 that he thinks that the signature was added to the original plate in a later stage, but removed again for the third series of copies; this doesn't seem to make much sense; besides, there are smaller stylistic changes, too; it is probably more likely that the same drawing or model image was imitated by different artists for the London publisher C. Shepherd because of high demand;

Israel Putnam,  (born January 7, 1718, Salem Village [now Danvers], Massachusetts [U.S.]—died May 29, 1790, Pomfret, Connecticut, U.S.), American general in the American Revolution.

After moving to Pomfret, Connecticut, about 1740, Putnam became a prosperous farmer. He saw service throughout the French and Indian War, being captured by Indians and rising to the rank of lieutenant colonel in 1759. By this time his numerous adventures on the frontier had given him a formidable reputation for strength and bravery. At the outbreak of the American Revolution in 1775, he was appointed a major general in the Continental Army. He distinguished himself at the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, but at the Battle of Long Island he commanded the divisions in Brooklyn that were defeated. In May 1777 he was put in charge of American defenses in the Hudson highlands, including Forts Montgomery and Clinton. When he abandoned these forts to the British soon afterward, he was faced with a court of inquiry, which nevertheless exonerated him. A paralytic stroke ended his active service in December 1779.

George Washington and others had originally placed high hopes in Putnam as a Continental commander, given his near-legendary feats as an Indian fighter. But Putnam proved disappointing as a tactician, being unable to plan and coordinate operations involving large numbers of troops. His dilatory execution of orders from Washington further diminished his effectiveness on the battlefield. Although brave, self-confident, and energetic, Putnam was not competent to fill the generalship that his popularity had brought him, and after 1777 Washington was forced to withhold important commands from him.
